<div class="title-block">
  <h1>Annotated: Paradigm&rsquo;s July 2024 Democratic Public Opinion Poll</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    By Justin Slaughter and Dominique Little.<br />
    <a href="https://policy.paradigm.xyz/writing/Dem-polling"
      >Originally published</a
    >
    on Paradigm&rsquo;s policy blog on August&nbsp;12,&nbsp;2024.
  </div>
  <div class="byline">
    Annotations by
    <a href="https://www.mollywhite.net">Molly White</a>. Published August 30,
    2024.<br />
    There is an
    <a href="https://www.citationneeded.news/paradigm-democrat-poll/"
      >audio version</a
    >
    of this annotation on <i>Citation Needed</i>.
  </div>
</div>
<div class="intro">
  <p>
    Paradigm, a cryptocurrency-focused venture capital firm, has joined the
    ranks of cryptocurrency companies and blockchain advocacy groups that are
    commissioning polls ostensibly to learn more about crypto sentiment among
    American voters.
  </p>
  <p>
    A previous poll, commissioned by the Digital Currency Group and published by
    the crypto lobbying group The Blockchain Association, summarized their
    findings in
    <a
      href="https://www.citationneeded.news/2024-cryptocurrency-election-spending/"
      >incredibly misleading ways</a
    >
    to try to pave the way for a narrative that there are a substantial number
    of single-issue voters who are likely to support pro-crypto candidates,
    regardless of other policy positions, in upcoming elections.
    <a
      href="https://www.citationneeded.news/when-did-cryptocurrency-become-a-voter-issue/#%E2%80%9C52-million-americans-own-crypto%E2%80%9D"
      >Another</a
    >, commissioned by Coinbase, is the source of &ldquo;data&rdquo; on crypto
    ownership that has been repeated by the industry, its lobbyists, and
    lawmakers alike, despite being extremely dubious.
  </p>
  <p>
    Instead of seeking to understand voter sentiment around crypto, these polls
    were nakedly designed to solicit desired responses. The responses, in turn,
    were summarized by the crypto firms in reports that were clearly designed to
    try to convince lawmakers and candidates that
    <a
      href="https://www.citationneeded.news/when-did-cryptocurrency-become-a-voter-issue/"
      >cryptocurrency is a major voter issue</a
    >, and that they risk losing potentially substantial support from their
    constitutents if they fail to prostrate themselves before the industry.
    After all, these are <i>hard numbers</i>, and numbers are
    <i>objective</i> and <i>concrete</i>!
  </p>
  <p>
    Does this poll, and the summary of its findings, suffer from the same flaws?
    Let&rsquo;s dig in.
  </p>
</div>
<div class="group first">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <mark aria-details="gravitating"
        >Democratic voters are increasingly gravitating towards crypto.</mark
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="gravitating" role="comment">
        <p>We&rsquo;ll come back to this &ldquo;primary takeaway&rdquo;.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      That&rsquo;s the primary takeaway of our new poll of registered Democrats,
      the complement to our poll of
      <a href="https://policy.paradigm.xyz/writing/GOP-Polling">Republicans</a>.
      from June. These results dovetail with recent reports that Democratic
      candidates for office and Members of Congress are becoming pro-crypto,
      <mark aria-details="following-lead"
        >indicating that political figures are following the lead of their
        voters.</mark
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="following-lead" role="comment">
        <p>
          There may be &ldquo;reports&rdquo; (generally from the industry) that
          candidates and incumbent Congresspeople are &ldquo;becoming
          pro-crypto&rdquo;, but I would definitely like to see some better
          support for the
          <a
            href="https://www.citationneeded.news/when-did-cryptocurrency-become-a-voter-issue/"
            >claim</a
          >
          that this is them &ldquo;following the lead of their voters&rdquo; and
          not, oh, I don&rsquo;t know, related to the
          <a href="https://followthecrypto.org/"
            >hundreds of millions of dollars available to candidates</a
          >
          who are deferential to the industry.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      For this release, the poll was conducted with the research firm
      <mark data-annotation-id="1" aria-details="mercury"
        >Mercury Analytics</mark
      >. Our poll was
      <mark data-annotation-id="2" aria-details="field">in the field</mark>
      from July 25th until August 1st, meaning that this data was collected in
      the days after President Joe Biden announced he would be stepping down as
      the Democratic nominee for President and Vice President Kamala Harris
      effectively locked up the nomination. We polled 804 self-identified
      Democratic registered voters for this poll, with a margin of error of
      3.5%. We also oversampled Black, Hispanic, and AAPI Democrats,
      <mark data-annotation-id="3" aria-details="oversample"
        >conducting 100 additional interviews with each of these audiences</mark
      >, to gain better insight into how non-white Democrats view crypto.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="mercury"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="1"
      >
        Mercury Analytics isn&rsquo;t listed on 538&rsquo;s pollster ratings
        list like
        <a
          href="https://www.citationneeded.news/when-did-cryptocurrency-become-a-voter-issue/#the-story"
          >DCG&rsquo;s pollster was</a
        >, but they also aren&rsquo;t a completely unknown quantity, having
        published research on topics ranging from vaping to 2020 presidential
        election debate sentiment. Their polls have been reported upon in
        <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> and elsewhere, though
        <a
          href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/youth-vaping-has-soared-in-2018-new-data-show-1537481424"
          >one such article</a
        >
        noted some flaws with survey design. Their CEO&rsquo;s June 2024 article
        about how &ldquo;<a
          href="https://www.fastcompany.com/91141369/ai-marketing-market-research"
          >AI is revolutionizing the market research industry</a
        >&rdquo; made me wonder if AI was involved in interpreting qualitative
        answers to <i>this</i> survey, as he advocated, but after speaking with
        Paradigm&rsquo;s policy team I learned that no qualitative interviews
        were performed.
      </div>
      <div class="annotation" id="field" role="comment" data-annotation-id="2">
        <p>
          I asked Paradigm for more detail about how the poll was conducted, and
          they informed me that it was conducted all online (unlike their
          <a href="https://policy.paradigm.xyz/writing/GOP-Polling"
            >June poll of Republicans</a
          >, which was conducted by phone and online). They do not publicly note
          this, nor does their poll summary address the skew that this likely
          introduces.
        </p>
        <p>
          A
          <a
            href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/files/2023-report-economic-well-being-us-households-202405.pdf"
            >May 2024 online survey by the Federal Reserve</a
          >
          notes: &ldquo;Because the survey is conducted online, the sample
          population may be more technologically connected than the overall
          population, which could increase the share of adults reporting use of
          emerging technologies such as cryptocurrencies.&rdquo; David Marker,
          fellow of the American Statistical Association and American Academy
          for the Advancement of Science and elected member of the International
          Statistical Institute,
          <a
            href="https://amycastor.com/2024/07/20/smear-campaigns-and-false-narratives-how-the-crypto-lobby-seeks-to-influence-us-politics-by-jake-donoghue/"
            >criticized</a
          >
          the DCG poll for failing to include such a disclaimer, commenting:
          &ldquo;Online surveys into crypto ownership can skew or misrepresent
          true figures, and they&rsquo;re inherently limited, as they
          don&rsquo;t factor in the digitally excluded on a topic that is
          directly related to digital comfort.&rdquo;
        </p>
        <p>
          At the very least, Paradigm should have disclosed the method by which
          respondents were surveyed, and preferably also proactively noted the
          potential skew this likely introduces.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="oversample"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="3"
      >
        For clarity&rsquo;s sake, I verified with Paradigm that the oversample
        brought the total number of respondents to around 1,100 people. The 300
        additional surveys were in addition to the 804&nbsp;people surveyed, not
        a part of that number.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <h3>
        Takeaway 1: Democratic crypto voters are up for grabs this November.
      </h3>
      <p>
        <mark aria-details="harris" data-annotation-id="1"
          >Making inroads with crypto owners could help Vice President Harris
          win back some wayward Democrats and increase her likelihood of
          winning.</mark
        >
        As of right now,
        <mark aria-details="dem-trump" data-annotation-id="2"
          >there are 1-2% of Democrats who may be leaning towards Trump due the
          Biden Administration&rsquo;s hostility to crypto</mark
        >.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="harris" role="comment" data-annotation-id="1">
        <p>
          They get right to the point about their goals with this survey. With
          polling that began just after Harris replaced Biden as the Democratic
          nominee and immediately began picking up steam, this poll seems to
          have been commissioned at least in part in hopes of convincing the
          Harris campaign, and those around her, that &ldquo;making inroads with
          crypto owners&rdquo; is something she needs to prioritize.
        </p>
        <p>
          It also fits with the timing of their previous poll, which was trying
          to convince Trump that <i>he</i> needed to attract Republicans who own
          crypto while he was leading in the polls.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="dem-trump"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="2"
      >
        <p>
          This is a bit of an odd data point, and odder still was the decision
          to highlight it as the very first finding, given it is also one of the
          weakest claims from this poll.
        </p>
        <p>
          First, let me remind you that they&rsquo;ve just stated a paragraph
          earlier that the margin of error in this poll is 3.5%.
        </p>
        <p>
          Second, the math doesn&rsquo;t really work out. I&rsquo;ve confirmed
          with Paradigm that they were calculating from the following graphic
          the number of &ldquo;non-Harris voters&rdquo; (<a href="#undecided"
            >more on that</a
          >
          in a second) who responded that the Biden admin was &ldquo;too
          hostile&rdquo; to cryptocurrency, and munging those two together to
          conclude that this segment thus &ldquo;may be leaning towards Trump
          due the Biden Administration&rsquo;s hostility to crypto&rdquo;.
          However, this figure actually comes out to about 2.7%, which is not
          within the stated &ldquo;1–2%&rdquo; range. (13% of 804 respondents is
          104.52; 21% of 104.52 is ~22; and 22 out of 804 people is ~2.7%.) I
          was informed they decided to provide a lower estimate in the summary
          than their polling suggested, because 2–3% &ldquo;felt too
          aggressive&rdquo;. But that raises the question: why bother polling if
          you&rsquo;re just going to change the numbers?
        </p>
        <p>
          Third, they did not ask any questions about whether the Biden
          admin&rsquo;s perceived hostility might actually push these people to
          vote for Trump, nor do they provide any details about how many of
          these &ldquo;non-Harris voters&rdquo; would consider voting for Trump
          in general.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content no-margin">
      <div class="in-text-image wide bordered">
