          /></a>
        </div>
        <p>
          Or perhaps scaling it down to the same proportions as the other chart,
          assuming the full width of the space represents 100%:
        </p>
        <div class="in-text-image wide bordered">
          <a
            href="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_1-3.png"
          >
            <img
              src="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_1-3.png"
              alt="Same as the first chart, but the blue 18% bar is now in proportion to a width of 100%, matching the second bar chart."
          /></a>
        </div>
        <p>Ahh, much better.</p>
      </div>
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="dem-poll-1"
        data-annotation-id="2"
        role="comment"
      >
        In the second bar chart, the designers of this report have for some
        reason opted to place the 52% &ldquo;don&rsquo;t know&rdquo; respondents
        between &ldquo;just about right&rdquo; and &ldquo;too hostile&rdquo;, as
        though it signifies &ldquo;somewhat too hostile&rdquo;.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          Of the 804 Democrats we polled,
          <mark aria-details="undecided"
            >13% said they were not voting for Harris as they are either voting
            for Trump, a third-party candidate, or are still undecided</mark
          >.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="undecided" role="comment">
        I verified with Paradigm that this 13% &ldquo;undecided&rdquo; figure is
        indeed the proportion of people who indicated they would be voting for
        Trump, a third-party candidate, or had not yet decided, but that they
        had <i>not</i> polled on whether these voters would choose not to vote
        for Harris. In my opinion, it&rsquo;s misleading to suggest in the
        summary that these people are all &ldquo;not voting for Harris&rdquo;
        (or refer to them throughout as &ldquo;non-Harris voters&rdquo;) given
        that they did not indicate that, and some of those undecided voters may
        well end up voting for Harris — as might some of those who indicated
        they would vote for a third-party candidate who later dropped out.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          <mark aria-details="trump-supporting" data-annotation-id="1">
            Trump-supporting Democrats</mark
          >
          are far more likely to
          <mark aria-details="have-bought" data-annotation-id="2"
            >have brought cryptocurrency</mark
          >
          than the rest of those polled. 18% of non-Harris Democrats have bought
          crypto, and Trump-supporting Democrats have bought at two times that
          rate.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="trump-supporting"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="1"
      >
        Paradigm verified that 5% of the self-identified Democrats in this poll
        indicated they would be voting for Trump.
      </div>
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="have-bought"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="2"
      >
        This figure seems to come from the later question in section 3 that asks
        &ldquo;Have you ever invested in, traded, or used a cryptocurrency such
        as Bitcoin or Ethereum?&rdquo; I don&rsquo;t love these types of
        questions because they include people like myself, who are highly
        skeptical of cryptocurrencies but own (or previously owned) some for
        research purposes. It also includes those who purchased crypto and then
        got rid of (or lost) it all; those who have used crypto for a single
        transaction; those who have just received crypto in promotional deals;
        etc. This is not necessarily a great measure of people who have strong
        and positive feelings about crypto, or of people who would support the
        kinds of policies generally supported by the industry.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          <mark aria-details="hostile">
            Additionally, 21% of non-Harris voters say that the Biden
            Administration has been &ldquo;a little too hostile&rdquo; or
            &ldquo;much too hostile&rdquo; on crypto.</mark
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="hostile" role="comment">
        If you were curious like I was: 7% of these &ldquo;non-Harris
        voters&rdquo; responded &ldquo;much too hostile&rdquo; and 14% responded
        &ldquo;a little too hostile&rdquo;. We&rsquo;re
        <i>really</i> in percent-of-a-percent territory here: we&rsquo;re
        talking about 7 people and 15 people (respectively). It&rsquo;s pretty
        wild that they&rsquo;re looking at 7 responses — 22 if we generously
        count those who don&rsquo;t feel as strongly — from a poll of more than
        800 people, and extrapolating that over the US population to claim that
        &ldquo;Democratic crypto voters are up for grabs this November&rdquo;.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <h3>
        Takeaway 2: Democrats are worried about losing purchasing power and
        being cut off from the financial system.
      </h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content empty"></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <p>
        <mark aria-details="fin-priv" data-annotation-id="1"
          >A core goal of crypto – giving people greater ability to maintain
          financial privacy</mark
        >
        – resonates with Democrats.
        <mark aria-details="contrary" data-annotation-id="2"
          >Contrary to some suppositions, Democratic voters recognize the
          dangers of mass surveillance.</mark
        >
      </p>
      <p>Financial privacy is a core belief for Democratic voters.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          72% of respondents agreed that &ldquo;personal financial transactions
          should generally be kept private, and only made available to
          government agencies when needed for specific purposes.&rdquo;
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="fin-priv"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="1"
      >
        This may be a <i>stated goal</i>, but it&rsquo;s far from a real-life
        feature of most popular cryptocurrencies. See my essays &ldquo;<a
          href="https://blog.mollywhite.net/abuse-and-harassment-on-the-blockchain/"
          >Abuse and harassment on the blockchain</a
        >&rdquo; and &ldquo;<a
          href="https://blog.mollywhite.net/anonymous-crypto-wallets/"
          >Anonymous cryptocurrency wallets are not so simple</a
        >&rdquo;, which go into more detail. In short, while banks keep records
        of financial transactions that they may later share with law
        enforcement, data on public blockchains is visible to anyone, including
        to law enforcement without a warrant. Blockchain analysis firms like
        Chainalysis (which has
        <a
          href="https://www.usaspending.gov/search/?hash=830eb292ad03ca0d59fc606284180839"
          >earned more than $80 million</a
        >
        from contracts with US federal government agencies alone, not to mention
        contracts with state-level organizations and non-US government and law
        enforcement clients)
        <a href="https://youtu.be/rz2x6ynCBi8?si=ERrvvlh9ASrqbfng&t=448"
          >like to brag</a
        >
        about just how easy crypto tracing is for them.
      </div>
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="contrary"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="2"
      >
        Who is supposing this other than Republican talking heads?
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          <mark aria-details="irs"
            >Just 15% took the view that &ldquo;personal financial transactions
            should generally be recorded in a place where it is easy for
            government agencies like the IRS to review
            transactions.&rdquo;</mark
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
      <div class="in-text-image wide bordered">
        <a href="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_2.png">
          <img
            src="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_2.png"
            alt="Thinking about the way people's financial transactions are handled, which of the following do you agree with more?
            72% Personal financial transactions should generally be kept private, and only made available to government agencies when needed for specific purposes
            13% Not sure
            15% Personal financial transactions should generally be recorded in a place where it is easy for government agencies like the IRS to review transactions"
        /></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="irs" role="comment">
        <p>
          This 15% is going to <i>love</i> blockchains, then.
          Cryptocurrency&rsquo;s reputation as a useful tool for tax evasion has
          primarily been a result of the IRS&rsquo;s lack of interest in
          scrutinizing once niche categories of transactions — and that is
          something that has been
          <a
            href="https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-updates-draft-version-of-form-1099-da-digital-asset-proceeds-from-broker-transactions-requests-comments-on-form-planned-for-2025"
            >changing in recent times</a
          >.
        </p>
        <p>
          Notably, this poll did not ask any questions about respondents&rsquo;
          opinions on using cryptocurrencies to achieve financial privacy, and
          instead is simply assuming that respondents who want financial privacy
          would support crypto, and vice versa.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          Additionally,
          <mark aria-details="repro" data-annotation-id="1"
            >78% of respondents said it was extremely or very important that
            people have a way to pay for reproductive care without making their
            transactions known to their state government or the federal
            government</mark
          >; only 6% of Democrats disagreed.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <div class="in-text-image wide bordered">
        <mark
          class="image-mark"
          aria-details="dem-poll-3"
          data-annotation-id="2"
        >
          <a
            href="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_3.png"
          >
            <img
              src="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_3.png"
              alt="How important is it for people to have a way to pay for reproductive care without making their transactions known to their state government or the federal government?
            53% Extremely important
            25% Very important
            16% Somewhat important
            4% Not that important
            2% Not at all important"
          /></a>
        </mark>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="repro" role="comment" data-annotation-id="1">
        <p>
          Okay, putting the sarcasm aside for a minute here: please
          <i>for the love of god</i> do not put your abortions on the
          blockchain! Do not try to pay for your or another person&rsquo;s
          abortion using crypto, or encourage others to do so! This is an
          incredibly dangerous idea, as states are working to criminalize not
          only abortion, but also punish those who try to provide aid to others
          who need them. While there are a handful of cryptocurrencies that seek
          to provide some privacy for those who transact with them, the vast
          majority of popular cryptocurrencies do not.
        </p>
        <p>
          Another thing: while it&rsquo;s good of Paradigm to note the
          importance of financial privacy in situations where people are seeking
          medical care that has been criminalized or may be criminalized in the
          future, they should perhaps consider also not funding the
          <a href="https://www.citationneeded.news/issue-63/#state-primaries"
            >campaign of a candidate</a
          >
          who has supported incredibly strict anti-abortion laws,
          <a
            href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/26/politics/blake-masters-abortion-arizona-senate/index.html"
            >described</a
          >
          abortion rights activists as &ldquo;demonic&rdquo;, and said that
          abortion is a &ldquo;religious sacrifice to these [abortion rights
          activists].&rdquo; (Paradigm
          <a href="https://www.followthecrypto.org/companies/paradigm"
            >contributed</a
          >
          $500,000 to the cryptocurrency super PACs, which have spent about
          $583,000 on
          <a href="https://www.followthecrypto.org/elections/AZ-H-08"
            >Blake Masters&rsquo;</a
          >
          fortunately unsuccessful Republican primary campaign in
          Arizona&rsquo;s District 8.)
        </p>
      </div>
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="dem-poll-3"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="2"
      >
        Okay, who decided it was a good idea to make the affirmative responses
        go from dark blue to light blue as the respondents&rsquo; level of
        agreement gets less strong, but then use the dark orange to mark
        &ldquo;not that important&rdquo; and light orange for &ldquo;not at all
        important&rdquo;? I just want to talk to them, I swear...
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <p>
        Nearly all Democrats are also worried about protecting their purchasing
        power, matching the views of Republicans and Independents:
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content empty"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          <mark aria-details="purhcasing-power"
            >80% of Democrats said it was &ldquo;very important&rdquo; or
            &ldquo;extremely important&rdquo; that their &ldquo;money maintains
            its purchasing power over time.&rdquo;</mark
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
      <div class="in-text-image wide bordered">
        <a href="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_4.png">
          <img
            src="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_4.png"
            alt="How important is it to you that your money maintains its purchasing power over time?
          44% Extremely important
          36% Very important
          16% Somewhat important
