<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <h3>
        Takeaway 3: Crypto is most popular among Democratic voters of color.
      </h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content empty"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <p>
        When Democrats come out as pro-crypto,
        <mark aria-details="non-white" data-annotation-id="1"
          >they are following the lead of their own non-white base voters, who
          view crypto positively</mark
        >.
        <mark aria-details="prev-polling" data-annotation-id="2">
          Previous
          <a href="https://policy.paradigm.xyz/writing/March-2024-Polling"
            >Paradigm polling</a
          ></mark
        >
        has shown that
        <mark aria-details="non-white-2" data-annotation-id="3"
          >crypto ownership and support is strongest among non-white voters, and
          that is also true among non-white Democrats</mark
        >.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>18% of Democrats have bought crypto in the past.</li>
        <li>
          This number rises to 22% among Black Democrats, 25% among Hispanic
          Democrats, and 27% among Asian American and Pacific Islander
          Democrats.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <div class="in-text-image wide bordered">
        <a href="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_5.png">
          <img
            src="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_5.png"
            alt="Have you ever invested in, traded, or used a cryptocurrency such as Bitcoin or Ethereum?
            Overall 18%
            White 15%
            Black 22%
            Hispanic 25%
            ΑΑΡΙ 27%"
        /></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="non-white"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="1"
      >
        <p>
          Paradigm seems to be using current or past ownership of
          cryptocurrencies as the metric by which they determine a person
          &ldquo;views crypto positively&rdquo;, which is
          <a href="#have-bought"
            >flawed for reasons I&rsquo;ve already described</a
          >.
        </p>
        <p>
          However, even if we put that aside and assume that the 18% figure (or
          15–27% when broken down by race) actually represents support for
          cryptocurrencies, it would seem that Democratic politicians who
          &ldquo;come out as pro-crypto&rdquo; would in fact be
          <i>failing</i> to follow the lead of the remaining 82% (or 73–85%) of
          their constituents who don&rsquo;t view crypto positively.
        </p>
        <p>
          It&rsquo;s also possible they&rsquo;re reaching this conclusion from
          the later question (not captured in a graphic), stating that 13–32% of
          respondents say that &ldquo;crypto plays a positive role in the U.S.
          economy&rdquo;. If that&rsquo;s the case, the inverse is roughly the
          same: 68–87% of respondents don&rsquo;t view crypto positively.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="prev-polling"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="2"
      >
        <p>
          The March 2024 Paradigm poll cited here claimed that &ldquo;19% of
          American registered voters say they&rsquo;ve bought crypto.&rdquo; It
          is generally an interesting exercise to compare crypto industry
          polling results to polls from outside the industry (though there are
          variations in question formulation, namely with some polls asking
          about
          <mark class="highlight-1">current crypto ownership</mark> vs.
          <mark class="highlight-2">ever having owned crypto</mark>):
        </p>
        <h4>Non-industry-funded polls</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href="">JPMorganChase, 2022</a>:
            <mark class="highlight-2"
              >15% of their American customers have conducted transfers to
              crypto accounts</mark
            >. (I suppose someone could argue that JPMorgan is an industry
            pollster, given their
            <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JPM_Coin"
              >blockchain forays</a
            >, but that is not their primary business. Take their numbers with
            grains of salt as you deem fit.)
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2023/04/10/majority-of-americans-arent-confident-in-the-safety-and-reliability-of-cryptocurrency/"
              >Pew Research Center, March 2023</a
            >:
            <mark class="highlight-2"
              >17% of American adults have ever invested in, traded or used a
              cryptocurrency</mark
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/files/2023-report-economic-well-being-us-households-202405.pdf"
              >Federal Reserve, 2023</a
            >:
            <mark class="highlight-1"
              >7% of American adults hold or use cryptocurrency</mark
            >
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>Industry-funded polls</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://a16z.com/prediction-for-the-new-year-a-web3-midterm/"
              >Andreessen Horowitz, December 2021</a
            >:
            <mark class="highlight-1"
              >20% of American registered voters own crypto</mark
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://pro.morningconsult.com/trackers/cryptocurrency-adoption-and-perspectives"
              >Coinbase, 2022–2024</a
            ><sup><a href="#footnote-1">1</a></sup
            >:
            <mark class="highlight-1"
              >18.2% of American adults own crypto (varies over time between 16%
              and 22%)</mark
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="https://policy.paradigm.xyz/writing/March-2024-Polling"
              >Paradigm, March 2024</a
            >:
            <mark class="highlight-2"
              >19% of American registered voters have ever invested in, traded
              or used a cryptocurrency such as Bitcoin or Ethereum</mark
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://theblockchainassociation.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/DCG_HarrisPoll-Research-Report.pdf"
              >DCG, April 2024</a
            >:
            <mark class="highlight-1"
              >14% of registered voters in six swing states own crypto</mark
            >;
            <mark class="highlight-2"
              >26% own or have previously owned crypto</mark
            >
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          To their credit, Paradigm&rsquo;s March poll is reasonably close to
          the Pew and JPMorgan surveys, particularly when compared to crypto
          industry surveys that have polled current crypto ownership and come in
          <i>way</i> higher than non-industry polls. In this poll, Paradigm asks
          about the amount of cryptocurrency respondents currently own later on,
          revealing that
          <mark class="highlight-1"
            >12% of their respondents <i>currently</i> own crypto</mark
          >
          (leaving 6% in the &ldquo;former owner&rdquo; bucket). This is quite
          high compared to the Federal Reserve&rsquo;s numbers, but considerably
          lower than the 20% figure Coinbase and others like to throw around.
        </p>
        <p>
          Paradigm also claimed to me that they&rsquo;ve found that providing
          examples of cryptocurrencies in their question (&ldquo;have you ever
          invested in, traded or used a cryptocurrency such as Bitcoin or
          Ethereum?&rdquo;) results in higher affirmative responses. This is
          surprising to me, since it would seem to suggest a significant number
          of people hold BTC or ETH but don&rsquo;t view them as
          cryptocurrencies.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="non-white-2"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="3"
      >
        <p>
          Other recent polls (including
          <a
            href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2023/04/10/majority-of-americans-arent-confident-in-the-safety-and-reliability-of-cryptocurrency/"
            >Pew&rsquo;s</a
          >) have had similar findings to Paradigm&rsquo;s: that people of color
          are somewhat more likely to have owned crypto than white respondents.
          This is generally treated by the cryptocurrency industry as a positive
          thing, and some influential crypto figures like to describe crypto as
          a particular opportunity for people of color to &ldquo;build
          generational wealth&rdquo; or access financial services they have
          historically not been able to access (sometimes using tactics that
          have been described as &ldquo;<a
            href="https://www.brookings.edu/articles/debunking-the-narratives-about-cryptocurrency-and-financial-inclusion/"
            >predatory inclusion</a
          >&rdquo;).
        </p>
        <p>
          However, the higher crypto ownership among people of color is a fairly
          recent development — and one that means that many of these investors
          bought in at all-time-highs in 2020 and 2021, with many later losing
          much of it in the 2022 crash. &ldquo;[R]ecent polls show a sharp
          decline in the share of Black Americans holding bitcoin, indicating
          that many folks might have bought high and sold low,&rdquo;
          <a
            href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/black-investors-bitcoin-cryptocurrency-crash/671750/"
            >reported</a
          >
          Annie Lowrey in <i>The Atlantic</i> in November 2022.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <p>
        To be clear, crypto is the most popular among non-white Democrats
        regardless of ownership.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content empty"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          <mark aria-details="positive"
            >28% of Black Democrats, 32% of Hispanic Democrats, and 27% of AAPI
            Democrats say that crypto plays a positive role in the U.S. economy.
            This is a massive jump compared to 13% of White Democrats who said
            the same.</mark
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="positive" role="comment">
        With polls like these, it&rsquo;s often informative to invert the
        numbers used in the conclusions they&rsquo;re trying to draw attention
        to. 68–87% of respondents <i>do not</i> agree that crypto plays a
        positive role in the U.S. economy. This is a significant majority, and
        it&rsquo;s worth considering why the authors of this report chose to
        focus on the minority of respondents who do agree.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <h4>
        Takeaway 4: Crypto ownership is likely to grow among Democrats in the
        next 12 months.
      </h4>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content empty"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <p>
        <mark aria-details="plan-to-buy" data-annotation-id="1"
          >More Democratic voters are saying they plan to buy crypto in the next
          12 months than have ever bought it before.</mark
        >
        If you needed additional proof that Democrats are warming to crypto,
        <mark aria-details="fire-bell" data-annotation-id="2">
          this is a fire bell in the night</mark
        >.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="plan-to-buy"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="1"
      >
        <p>
          This is inaccurate. As the poll states in the second bullet point
          below, 17% of non-crypto-holding Democrats say they plan to purchase
          crypto in the next year, whereas 18% of Democrats overall have already
          bought crypto.
        </p>
        <p>
          I suspect this is an artifact of an earlier error in this poll
          summary. Bullet point two
          <a
            href="https://web.archive.org/web/20240812163928/https://policy.paradigm.xyz/writing/Dem-polling"
            >originally read</a
          >: &ldquo;This means about 27% of Democrats who haven&rsquo;t yet
          bought crypto are likely to buy in the next year.&rdquo; That seemed
          extremely high to me as a percentage of non-crypto-holding
          respondents, and after I inquired, Paradigm corrected the bullet point
          to 17%. However, they seem to have missed this conclusory sentence up
          here when making that correction.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="fire-bell"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="2"
      >
        <p>
          <a
            href="https://pro.morningconsult.com/trackers/cryptocurrency-adoption-and-perspectives"
            >Polling</a
          >
          by Morning Consult (the firm that has been doing the polling for both
          Andreessen Horowitz and Coinbase mentioned above)<sup
            ><a href="#footnote-1">1</a></sup
          >
          has claimed that the percentage of respondents who were &ldquo;likely
          to purchase cryptocurrency in the next month&rdquo; has hovered
          relatively stably between 20% and 26% ever since they began polling in
          January 2022. However, the same polls <i>also</i> suggest that the
          percentage of respondents who hold crypto has remained relatively
          stable, with some increase going into April 2023, and some decline
          over the past year. The
          <a
            href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/files/2023-report-economic-well-being-us-households-202405.pdf"
            >Federal Reserve survey</a
          >
          shows declining cryptocurrency ownership from 2021 to 2023.
        </p>
        <p>
          This suggests that, far from being a &ldquo;fire bell in the
          night&rdquo;, this may just be a poor indicator of actual future
          adoption. Either that, or people are getting out of crypto in such
          numbers that they are more than offsetting these supposed new
          adopters.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          <mark aria-details="likely"
            >9% of Democrats say they are very likely to invest in crypto in the
            next year, and another 18% of Democrats are somewhat likely to
            invest.</mark
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="likely" role="comment">
        This is out of all respondents, including those who do not currently own
        cryptocurrencies. It&rsquo;s probably safe to assume that some (though
        perhaps not many) of those 9% &ldquo;very likely&rdquo; respondents do
        not currently hold crypto, but even if we generously assume every single
        person in that 9% already holds, it seems noteworthy that at least half
        of the 18% of respondents who said they currently hold crypto are at
        best lukewarm about buying more of it going into the next year.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          27% of Democrats are likely to buy in the next year, including about
          17% of Democrats who have never previously bought.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content empty"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content no-margin">
      <div class="in-text-image wide bordered">
        <mark class="image-mark" aria-details="dem-poll-6">
          <a
            href="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_6.png"
          >
            <img
              src="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_6.png"
              alt="How likely are you to invest in cryptocurrency in the next 12 months?
            Very likely 9%
            Somewhat likely 18%
            Not that likely 18%
            Not at all likely 54%"
          /></a>
        </mark>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="dem-poll-6" role="comment">
        Again, the <i>other</i> numbers hidden away in the graphic here seem
        notable. A full half of respondents slammed the &ldquo;hell no&rdquo;
        button when asked if they might like to try out crypto in the upcoming
        year. Almost 3 in 4 were varying degrees of unlikely to get involved.
        This roughly aligns with
        <a
          href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2023/04/10/majority-of-americans-arent-confident-in-the-safety-and-reliability-of-cryptocurrency/"
          >Pew&rsquo;s</a
        >
        findings in 2023 that 75% of Americans who have heard of
        cryptocurrencies are not confident in their safety and reliability.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <h4>
        Takeaway 5: Crypto ownership among Democrats is
        <mark aria-details="parity" data-annotation-id="1"
          >approaching parity</mark
        >
        with stock ownership and
        <mark aria-details="continues-grow" data-annotation-id="2"
          >continues to grow</mark
        >.
      </h4>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="parity" role="comment" data-annotation-id="1">
        Even assuming these numbers are good (<a href="#stock">see later</a>),
        it is not at all clear to me how 12% current ownership of crypto can be
        interpreted as &ldquo;approaching parity&rdquo; with 33% ownership of
        stocks. I guess if you had historical data that showed &lt;12% current
        ownership, then any increase would be &ldquo;approaching parity&rdquo;
        in a sense... but Paradigm doesn&rsquo;t mention having any historical
        data besides the polls they conducted on different demographic groups
        earlier this year. Year-over-year data from other pollsters show crypto
        ownership remaining roughly flat (<a
          href="https://pro.morningconsult.com/trackers/cryptocurrency-adoption-and-perspectives"
          >crypto industry polls</a
        >) or decreasing (<a
          href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/files/2023-report-economic-well-being-us-households-202405.pdf"
          >non-crypto industry polls</a
        >).
      </div>
      <div
        class="annotation"
        id="continues-grow"
        role="comment"
        data-annotation-id="2"
      >
        Again, not clear where this claim is coming from, given their lack of
        historical data. My best guess is they&rsquo;re just going off of the
        respondents who said they were likely to purchase crypto going forward —
        which,
        <a href="#fire-bell">as I said</a>, seems to be a dubious indicator of
        actual growth. Remember <a href="#gravitating">at the beginning</a> when
        I said we would come back to the opening claim that &ldquo;Democratic
        voters are increasingly gravitating towards crypto&rdquo;? This is that
        moment.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <p>
        Based on our data, millions of Democratic voters own tens of thousands
        of dollars of crypto. These are significant holdings for any asset, the
        kind that drive voting behavior:
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content empty"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          At present, 18% of Democrats have bought crypto, with 12% currently
          owning and 6% having previously bought it but no longer owning it.
          <mark aria-details="stock"
            >33% of respondents currently own stock.</mark
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="stock" role="comment">
        This is <i>significantly</i> lower than the numbers reported by
        <a
          href="https://news.gallup.com/poll/266807/percentage-americans-owns-stock.aspx"
          >Gallup</a
        >, which showed that 61% of Americans owned stocks<sup
          ><a href="#footnote-2">2</a></sup
        >
        in 2023, with that number ranging between 50% and 60% for the past
        decade. However, Paradigm&rsquo;s number is closer to the results for a
        question from a 2019 poll by
        <a
          href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2020/09/25/few-in-u-s-owned-stocks-outside-of-401ks-in-2019-fewer-said-market-had-a-big-impact-on-their-view-of-economy/"
          >Pew Research</a
        >, which found that 35% of respondents <i>directly</i> owned stocks
        outside of retirement accounts, and 55% had IRAs, 401(k)s, or similar
        retirement accounts.<sup><a href="#footnote-3">3</a></sup> This makes me
        think people may have been interpreting the question by Paradigm in the
        latter way, but the definition probably should have been made clearer
        both in the question and in this poll summary.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          <mark aria-details="last-year"
            >8% of Democrats first bought crypto within the last year</mark
          >, with 3% having bought crypto in the past few months and 2% buying
          in the past few weeks.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="last-year" role="comment">
        This is surprisingly high when compared to their finding that 12% own
        crypto, full stop. This may support the
        <a href="#fire-bell">hypothesis I mention above</a> that a substantial
        number of people who bought in a year or more ago have since sold off
        those holdings.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          8% of respondents say
          <mark aria-details="1000"
            >they currently own more $1000 in crypto</mark
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="1000" role="comment">
        I wonder how many of these respondents could feasibly liquidate their
        crypto holdings for the dollar amounts they&rsquo;re estimating, and how
        many just have
        <a
          href="https://blog.mollywhite.net/cryptocurrency-market-caps-and-notional-value/#price"
          >&ldquo;$1,000&rdquo; on paper</a
        >.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          <mark aria-details="10k"
            >5% of respondents own more than $10,000 in crypto.</mark
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content">
      <div class="annotation" id="10k" role="comment">
        <p>
          These figures don&rsquo;t really line up with other estimates, such as
          from a
          <a
            href="https://www.jpmorganchase.com/institute/all-topics/financial-health-wealth-creation/dynamics-demographics-us-household-crypto-asset-cryptocurrency-use"
            >2022 JPMorgan survey</a
          >
          that claimed that &ldquo;the median gross amount transferred to crypto
          accounts over the period 2015 through the first half of 2022 was
          approximately $620&rdquo;. They also found that, out of people who
          hold crypto, about 11–15% of them have transferred one month of income
          or more into crypto accounts, and 4–6% have transfered three or more
          months of income. Doing some <i>extremely rough</i> napkin math: the
          median monthly income is approximately $5,000. JPMorgan found that 15%
          of their sample had transferred funds to crypto accounts. 11–15% of
          that 15% is 1.65–2.25% of the total sample who have transferred, based
          on median income, $5,000 or more. 4–6% of that 15% is 0.6–0.9% who
          have transferred, based on median income, $15,000 or more.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content">
      <ul>
        <li>
          Underscoring crypto&rsquo;s popularity among non-white Democrats, 10%
          of Hispanic Democrats polled own more than $10,000 in crypto, and 9%
          of AAPI Democrats own more than $10,000 in crypto.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="right">
    <div class="content empty"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="group">
  <div class="left">
    <div class="content no-margin">
      <div class="in-text-image wide bordered">
        <mark class="image-mark" aria-details="dem-poll-7">
          <a
            href="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_7.png"
          >
            <img
              src="https://storage.mollywhite.net/micro/dem_polling_image_7.png"
              alt="Please indicate how much cryptocurrency you currently own.
              Does not own cryptocurrency 88%
              Less than $1,000
              4%
